National Cooperation Called for 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 7 (KCNA) -- The U.S. is persistently pursuing its policy of war of aggression against the DPRK while brandishing its nuclear club. But this will prove futile in face of the concerted efforts of the Korean nation to implement the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration regarding it as the only weapon for carving out the destiny of the nation.
Rodong Sinmun Sunday says this in a signed article. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 National cooperation is a sure guarantee for protecting peace on the Korean Peninsula and successfully paving the way for the movement for independent reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The principle of national independence, the principle of strongly opposing flunkeyism and dependence on outsiders, represents the main spirit of national cooperation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The principle of national independence is the master key to settling the national issue. Peace and reunification on the Korean Peninsula should be achieved at any cost by the concerted efforts of the Korean nation as the master responsible for them because they are an issue related to its sovereignty and destiny. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 No illusion and dependence on outsiders should be allowed. They only lead to national ruin. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is an essential prerequisite to national cooperation to achieve the great unity of the whole nation based on the love for the country and the nation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the Koreans place the love for the country and the nation, the common denominator of a homogenous nation, above anything else and get united based on it irrespective of ideology and system, it is possible to realize effective cooperation among Koreans whereby they can defeat any formidable enemy in the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 National cooperation calls for unity based on the love for the country and the nation with the principle of national independence as its main spirit. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
This provides a sure guarantee for protecting peace and security of the nation and successfully conducting the movement for independent reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 National cooperation means independence, peace and reunification. Whoever loves the country and the nation and is concerned about their destiny should unite as one irrespective of ideology, political view, religious belief, class and social strata and abode.

National Championships Held 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 7 (KCNA) -- National championships were held in Pyongyang, Hamhung, Sariwon, Haeju and other places in September and October.
 The participants competed in over 40 main events. New national records were set in 22 events of shooting, weightlifting, swimming and archery competitions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Players of the April 25 Sports Group emerged winners in men and women basketball, volleyball, table-tennis, marathon, men's handball, boxing, gymnastic and Korean wrestling events. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Amnokgang Sports Group placed first in the women's football match and weightlifting, the Pyongyang City Sports Group in men's football match and rhythmic gymnastic contest and the Kigwancha Sports Group in men's tennis, baseball and women's gymnastic events. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Men and women players of the Sports Group of the Ministry of Fisheries came first in water polo, diving and synchronized swimming events, players of the Sports Group of the Ministry of Commerce in women's boxing and acrobatic gymnastic events and men and women players of the Sports Group of the Pyongyang Railway Bureau in the roller hockey game and women players of the Sports Group of Han Tok Su University of Light Industry in Pyongyang in the tennis game.

Reception Given in Honor of Ugandan Government Delegation 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 7 (KCNA) -- A reception was given by the Ministry of the People's Armed Forces in honor of the visiting Ugandan government delegation Saturday evening.
 Present there on invitation were members of the delegation led by Amama Mbabazi, minister of Defence of Uganda. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there were Vice Marshal of the Korean People's Army (KPA) Kim Il Chol, minister of the People's Armed Forces, Kim Jong Gak, vice-minister of the People's Armed Forces, general officers and officers of the KPA. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Il Chol said in his speech that the DPRK visit of the Ugandan government delegation is taking place at a time when the political and military relations are developing between the DPRK and Uganda at a new level, adding that this reflects the desire of the Ugandan government and people to see stronger friendship and cooperation between the two countries, cooperation and exchange in the military field in particular. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Recalling that the U. S. is perpetrating high-handed and arbitrary practices in various parts of the world quite contrary to the common desire of humankind to live in a peaceful and stable world, he noted the reality proves that one's own strong military power alone can protect the destiny of one's country and nation and guarantee social stability and development. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He expressed the belief that the visit of the delegation would mark an important occasion in putting the bilateral state and military ties on a new higher level. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Amama Mbabazi in his speech expressed thanks to Supreme Commander of the KPA Kim Jong Il, general secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea and chairman of the National Defence Commission of the DPRK, for having given assistance, material and moral, to Uganda. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He said that no nation can exist without armed forces for self-defence, adding that Uganda has positively supported the stand of the DPRK on increasing its defence capability. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He expressed solidarity with the Korean army and people in their struggle to achieve the reunification of the country, hoping that the exchange and cooperation between the two countries would grow stronger.

U.S. Forces in S. Korea Termed Aggressor and Wrecker of Peace 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 7 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the UN Headquarters clarified once again some time ago that the U.S. forces present in south Korea are not "UN forces" but the U.S.-led "combined forces". The "UN Forces Command" in south Korea, however, let loose balderdash that those nations which signed the 1953 armistice agreement would restore the alliance to continue to perform their role as UN peace-keeping force if the armistice agreement is scrapped and hostile acts are resumed. This reminds one of a thief crying "Stop the thief!"
 Rodong Sinmun Sunday says in a signed article in this regard: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is only the United States that claims its forces in south Korea are "UN forces" and let them go under their helmets.
 Those U.S. forces are a huge group of aggressors and a strangler of independence and democracy and a wrecker of peace. 
 The U.S. imperialists have desperately worked to perpetuate the division of Korea and ignite a new war on the Korean Peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. has resorted to vicious obstructive moves to bar the DPRK government's proposals for reunification from being materialized. The U.S. forces in south Korea have staged frantic exercises for a war of aggression, deliberately straining the situation in Korea. The Bush forces, in particular, have worked hard to lay an international siege to the DPRK and isolate and stifle it, vociferating about its "nuclear and missile threat". &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Decades have passed since the adoption of the UN resolution calling for the withdrawal of the U.S. forces from south Korea but the U.S. has not yet implemented it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. is a heinous enemy of independence and peace as it has left no means untried to carry out its policy of war of aggression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is preposterous for the Bush bellicose forces to try to justify their policy to perpetuate their military presence in south Korea and stifle the DPRK while talking about the "nuclear threat" from it .It is a blatant challenge to justice and peace.

Nat'l Scientific Idea Contest among Students of Middle Schools No.1
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Phyongsong, November 5 (KCNA) -- A national scientific idea contest among students of middle schools No.1 was held in Phyongsong, South Phyongan Province from November 2 to 5.
 It brought together at least 400 students chosen at provincial competitions. Entries included more than 640 works of clever and peculiar creation and invention, including science fictions, science fiction paintings, scientific essays and programs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Winners at the contest were 10 students from Kim Jong Suk Middle School No. 1 in Phyongsong, South Phyongan Province, Kum Song School, Kang Pan Sok Middle School No. 1 and Pyongyang Unjong Middle School No. 1 in Pyongyang, Sariwon Middle School No. 1 in North Hwanghae Province and Amnokgang Middle School No.1 in Sinuiju, North Phyongan Province. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The results of the contest were announced at Kim Jong Suk Middle School No. 1 on Friday. Letters of commendation and prizes were awarded to the successful students.

Chinese Defense Minister on Sino-Korean Friendship
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beijing, November 4 (KCNA) -- It is the firm stand of the party and government of China to further develop the Sino-Korean friendship, and the cooperative ties between the two armies will grow stronger in the future, too, for the sake of the blood-sealed bilateral friendship.
 Chinese Defense Minister Cao Gangchuan, vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission of the People's Republic of China, said this when meeting with the DPRK delegation headed by Kim Sang Ik, vice-minister of the People's Armed Forces, on Nov. 4 which was participating in the security policy meeting of the ASEAN Regional Forum in Beijing. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The two countries are maintaining the special and long-standing friendly ties, he said, adding that the friendship provided by President Kim Il Sung and the leaders of the elder generation of China is unbreakable as it stood all tests of history. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Chinese people are pleased with the fact that the DPRK, a friendly neighbor, is successfully building a great prosperous powerful nation under the leadership of Kim Jong Il, he noted.

New Films for Children Produced
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 6 (KCNA) -- The April 26 Children's Film Studio has produced a number of films for children helpful to their upbringing and education over the last three decades since leader Kim Jong Il clearly indicated the road to be followed by the creation of juvenile films on Nov. 6, Juche 63 (1974).
 In this period creators of the studio have produced hundreds of juvenile films based on fairy tales and fables suitable for the ages and mental qualities of pre-school and school children. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Among them are "A Gold Nugget and Maize Cakes", "The Hedgehog Beats the Tiger", "Hills of Bears and Rabbits", "Farmer and Skewbald Dog" and "The Millet Tree." These films tell them what is good and evil and justice and injustice and convince them that creative labour alone brings one rich fruits. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The films include serial films of "A Winged Horse," "Blue Spring," "The Boy General" and serials of "A Squirrel and a Hedgehog." They implant into the minds of children warm patriotism and towering hatred for the enemy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Serial films of "The Clever Raccoon Dog" and "The Pail Made by Turtle" and other films help the kindergarteners and primary school children consolidate what they have learned at lessons.

U.S. Obstructions to Construction of Kaesong Industrial Zone Assailed
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, November 6 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the Korean National Economic Cooperation Federation issued a statement Saturday bitterly denouncing the U.S. obstructions to the construction of the Kaesong Industrial Zone in the name of all Koreans desirous of national reconciliation, unity and independent reunification of the country.  The statement said:
 The U.S. has so far hindered its construction by hook or by crook but it is the first time that officials concerned of its government openly let loose a string of nonsensical remarks intended to obstruct the project and pressurized south Korea to adjust the tempo of the project depending on the prospect of settling the nuclear issue. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 These moves were prompted by its great displeasure with the fact that the project is set to enter the phase of full-scale construction soon despite the whole gamut of its obstructions and by its sinister aim to woo south Korea to earnestly join in implementing the hard-line policy it has pursued toward the DPRK over the nuclear issue and the human rights issue. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 .The U.S. is not entitled to say this or that about what the Koreans build on their land, the statement said, urging all the Koreans to be vigilant against the U.S. high-handed moves for domination and interference. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The statement called upon all the Koreans in the north and the south to turn out in the anti-U.S. struggle to defend the dignity and the sovereignty of the nation under the uplifted banner of the June 15 joint declaration and decisively deter the U.S. from obstructing the construction of the zone for the present.
